clusters.title: Emergency warnings issued as severe thunderstorm hits Melbourne

items.title: Emergency warnings issued as severe thunderstorm hits Melbourne
items.standfirst: Emergency warnings have been declared for parts of the city.
items.content: Residents in parts of Melbourne have been told to stay indoors as Victoria is battered by severe thunderstorms and the threat of flash flooding.Large parts of Melbourne's north, including Preston, Coburg and Craigieburn have been issued with an emergency warning from Vic Emergency this afternoon as a massive storm sweeps over the city.The message told residents in the impacted areas to "stay indoors" .LATEST: Remains found in search for kidnapped Sydney grandfatherAn emergency warning was also made for Warburton, a town just to the east of Melbourne.Melbourne Airport in the city's northern fringes was also battered by rain, with a large blanket of fog also spreading over the tarmac.It comes as Victoria's northern and central areas are also hit by heavy rainfall and damaging windsThe Bureau of Meteorology has had severe weather warnings in place for much of the state, including Melbourne, and issued a severe thunderstorm alert at around 2.30pm.NATIONAL: Design for Trump's first tower resort in Australia revealed"Very dangerous thunderstorms likely to produce intense rainfall that may lead to dangerous and life-threatening flash flooding were detected near Craigieburn and Warburton," it said.Around 38mm of rain was recorded in Spring Hill in a one hour and 15 minute period to 2pm. Six-hourly rainfall totals between 40 and 70 millimetres are possible, sparking a severe weather warning for heavy rainfall across places like Echuca, Bendigo, Seymour, Mount Buller, Warragul and the Melbourne metropolitan area.BOM senior meteorologist Angus Hines said flash flooding was possible through the Melbourne metropolitan region.Melbourne's western suburbs are particularly in danger of heavy rainfall, according to the Bureau's current severe weather warning.Warnings for livestock safety in rural areas have also been issued. Conditions are expected to move through eastern parts of Victoria and potentially south-eastern parts of NSW tomorrow. An initial flood watch is in place for North East, Central and Gippsland catchments.The system is also expected to push into Queensland's western Channel Country, affecting Birdsville, Eromanga, Bulloo Downs and the surrounds.There are already a number of flood warnings across the sunshine state due to recent rainfall.More rain and thunderstorms are also forecast today for much of northern and western Queensland, and there are warnings of widespread riverine flooding.The weather system is being driven by a low-pressure system bringing tropical moisture from central Australia, coupled with a cold front from the south.The low is expected to linger until at least the end of the week and possibly into next week, Hines said, though its impact on eastern Australia is expected to shift northward.Sydney will face the possibility of heavy rain from tomorrow afternoon. Emergency services are urging communities to prepare their properties before the storm by tying down loose outdoor items, clearing gutters and downpipes and parking cars undercover or away from trees.Motorists and commuters are warned to drive safely, allow extra travel time and be alert to allow extra travel time and stay alert for hazards. These hazards could include fallen trees, debris, damaged power lines and localised flash flooding."If severe weather is impacting your area, consider delaying travel where possible and staying indoors until conditions improve. Never drive through floodwater," VICSES chief officer of operations Alistair Drayton said.READ MORE: One award after another for Oscar front-runner at BAFTAsVictoria had a taste of the extreme weather on Sunday, with parts of the state battered by up to 40 millimetres of rain in the 24 hours to 9am yesterday.There was localised flash flooding in the Wodonga area, sparking 90 calls for assistance from VICSES.All up, SES volunteers responded to about 250 requests for assistance across the state between midday on Sunday and 10am yesterday."Thank you to the dedicated volunteers who worked throughout last night to assist impacted communities and remain ready to respond as further storms approach this week," Drayton said.Communities in areas recently impacted by bushfires have been warned of elevated flash flooding warnings. Burnt ground does not absorb water effectively, meaning runoff can occur quickly and without warning, the State Control Centre said.What was set to be a record-breaking dry summer across swaths of inland Australia has ended dramatically, with a torrential downpour bringing widespread flooding in the final days of summer. Before last weekend, much of inland Australia had not seen any rainfall for two to three months.An area the size of Greenland is on flood watch, from the top of the Northern Territory, into Queensland, NSW and down into agricultural regions of South Australia.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

clusters.title: NSW Transport releases footage of multiple close calls on roads across the state

items.title: NSW Transport releases footage of multiple close calls on roads across the state
items.standfirst: Between 2021 and 2025, there have been 45 fatalities from bus crashes across NSW .
items.content: Transport NSW has issued a "stark reminder" for pedestrians and motorists to remain alert, releasing footage of multiple close encounters on roads across the state as part of a safety campaign.The Be Bus Aware campaign is a strategy aimed at raising awareness surrounding the safety of NSW's most accessible form of transport.Transport for NSW Coordinator-General, Howard Collins, said more than 345 million trips are taken by bus each year across more than 800 of the vehicles statewide.LATEST: Human remains found in search for kidnapped Sydney grandfather"Buses are large, heavy vehicles and can't stop quickly, so all road users need to give them space," Collins said."Do not cut in front of or tailgate a bus, and take extra care when travelling in a bus's blind spot, as the driver may not be able to see you."The footage released today is a stark reminder for both motorists and pedestrians to always be bus aware."When out walking, stay alert."Cross the road at a safe place, such as a pedestrian crossing or traffic lights, or somewhere with a good line of sight, to see approaching traffic, and so they can see you, and never step out in front of a bus."READ MORE: Three people hospitalised after truck ploughs into front yard on busy Melbourne roadBetween 2021 and 2025, there have been 45 fatalities from bus crashes across NSW .Among the deaths were 12 drivers of other vehicles, 10 pedestrians and four motorcyclists. As part of Bus Safety Week, NSW Transport will raise awareness by displaying safety messages across social media, audio messages, visual signage at train stations and on major overhead roads .NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

clusters.title: Royal commission into antisemitism and social cohesion begins

items.title: Royal commission into antisemitism and social cohesion begins
items.standfirst: Commissioner Bell said she will "conduct the inquiry as expeditiously as possible" so that a full report is complete no later than one year after the Bondi terror attack.
items.content: The antisemitism royal commission has begun its first public hearing, with Commissioner Virginia Bell AC SC saying it will take no longer than a year to complete. The Royal Commission on Antisemitism and Social Cohesion began with Bell making an opening statement explaining how she will approach the inquiry."I acknowledge the importance of addressing antisemitism within the Australian community," Bell said.READ MORE: Remains found in search for kidnapped Sydney grandfather Chris BaghsarianBell said she will "conduct the inquiry as expeditiously as possible" so that a full report is complete no later than one year after the Bondi terror attack that launched the investigation.Other members of the senior counsel will also make short statements to open the hearing at Sydney's Law Courts building, however, no testimony or evidence will be presented today.The inquiry was officially declared on January 9 by Prime Minister Anthony Albanese and an interim report will be submitted by April 30.READ MORE: Baby boomers set to pass on $175 billion a year in willsThe full report is set to be released by December 14. Bell was appointed by the prime minster to lead the royal commission, stating that she would do an "outstanding job". "There is no one, though, of Virginia Bell's standing. The only former High Court justice who has been raised, the only person who has that background in criminal law, someone who is widely respected across the board," he told Today earlier this year.Throughout the inquiry, people will be allowed to share their life experiences over the duration of the commission through submissions and public hearings.
